{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Agentic code-review capability for rebar (off by default, source-separated), dogfooded via the Gerrit LLM-Review gate\n\n## Context\nBuild the agentic code-review capability as a SEPARATE, OFF-BY-DEFAULT rebar capability whose source is clearly isolated so it has no effect when disabled. It CONSUMES the shared **four-pass review kernel** (evidence -> verify -> decide -> coach) and is enforced through Gerrit's `LLM-Review` label on the AWS-hosted environment. Dogfooding on rebar itself is the success criterion.\n\n## Realignment (2026-06) ‚Äî this epic now CONSUMES a shipped kernel\nThis epic was written against a \"three-pass framework being built in epic `9da1` (OPEN)\". That is stale on two counts, corrected here (closed prerequisite epics are NOT reopened):\n\n- **The framework grew a 4th pass and SHIPPED.** `9da1` (\"three-pass; migrate existing reviewers\") was SUPERSEDED by `3316`/vivid-gang-day ‚Äî the **four-pass review KERNEL** (Pass-1 finder evidence; Pass-2 separate binary verifier; Pass-3 deterministic decide; Pass-4 affirmative coach) ‚Äî which is **CLOSED** and shipped as `src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/` (`verify.py` / `decide.py` / `coach.py`). `3316` explicitly `blocks` this epic and `docs/review-kernel.md` names b744 as \"the second consumer\". So b744 is no longer a from-scratch passes build ‚Äî it is a **kernel CONSUMER**: supply the per-gate plug-ins and call `verify_findings` / `pass3_over_findings` / `coach` directly.\n- **`code_review.py` is not a migration target ‚Äî it is a throwaway single-pass demo to RETIRE.** Today it does select-by-glob -> parallel reviewers -> `aggregate_findings` -> `finalize_findings`, with NO Pass-2/3/4. The deliverable is the kernel-consuming gate; the single-pass `aggregate_findings`-only route is removed (no half-migration).\n\n## Current substrate (shipped PRECONDITIONS vs this epic's NEW work)\nSHIPPED (build on; do not rebuild):\n- The **four-pass kernel** `review_kernel` (`3316`) + its documented consumer seam (`docs/review-kernel.md`): Pass-2 `verify_findings(findings, *, context, run_chunk, window_tokens, est_tokens, headroom)` + the single `verification` contract; Pass-3 `pass3_decide` / `pass3_over_findings(..., threshold_for)`; Pass-4 `coach(surviving, registry, *, pick, active_triggers)` + `MOVE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA` / `validate_move_registry` (with the `applies_when` field) + `VERIFIER_RULES_SCAFFOLD`. Verified gate-agnostic (consumes a code move-catalog + code findings directly).\n- The **provider-agnostic `PydanticAIRunner`** (`e6d9`) + the **v3 workflow engine** (steps/branch/batch/map/loop, `RunnerAgentStep`, `ProductionBatchRunner`, `gate_dispatch`).\n- **Contract-bearing code reviewer prompts** (`da27`): `code_quality` / `security` / `tests` front-matter prompts with `applies_to` globs + a derived index + CI drift gate.\n- The **grounding oracle + detector registry** (`8f6c`): the fail-open evidence oracle + an extensible detector registry (built-in + project `.rebar/detectors/`).\n\nNEW work (this epic):\n- The four-pass code-review GATE that consumes the kernel (diff context-assembler, finder/verify/coach prompts, code move-catalog, per-criterion thresholds) + the thin `gates/code-review.yaml` + `gate_dispatch.produce_code_review_verdict`.\n- The OVERLAY catalog (the ~11 specialist reviewers drafted in the catalog comments) + the base->overlay ESCALATION mechanism (below).\n- Secrets / High-Critical-security DETECTORS behind the grounding oracle's detector envelope (or wrap gitleaks/semgrep), with FAIL-CLOSED posture for the hard auto-block.\n- SOURCE-SEPARATION into an optional module preserving the MCP `review_code` tool + `rebar review-code` CLI via re-export.\n- The Gerrit `LLM-Review` voter wiring.\n\n## Design ‚Äî four-pass consumer + base->overlay escalation (mechanism PROVEN on the v3 engine)\nWorkflow shape (the same shape plan-review runs, plus a second agent-driven finder round):\n\n```\ndiff\n -> assemble_diff (uses)                  # diff + changed_files context        [NEW diff assembler]\n -> triggers      (uses: overlay_triggers)# Round-A glob/keyword overlay flags   [EXISTING op]\n -> base          (agent, standalone)     # base reviewer: findings + recommend_overlays\n -> round_a       (batch, when:=triggers) # deterministically-triggered overlays\n -> union         (uses: overlay_union)   # (glob U base.recommend) - already-run, capped, ONE-HOP  [NEW ~30-LOC op]\n -> round_b       (batch, when:=union)    # the ESCALATED overlays (agent-triggered)\n -> merge         (uses)                  # base + round_a + round_b findings\n -> verify (Pass-2) -> decide (Pass-3) -> coach (Pass-4)   # all kernel\n```\n\nOverlay activation = UNION of (a) overlays whose deterministic triggers (`applies_to` globs / content signatures) match the diff, and (b) overlays the BASE reviewer escalates to via a bounded `recommend_overlays: [{overlay_id, reason}]` signal, `overlay_id` constrained to the FIXED catalog enum. A DETERMINISTIC orchestrator takes the union (minus already-run), caps it (top-N), dispatches Round B, and ALL findings (base + Round-A + Round-B) flow into the SAME Pass-2 verifier + Pass-3 deterministic gate. Bounds: ONE HOP (overlays do not re-escalate); per-change CAP; escalation lives on the recall/selection side only (a false escalation costs one extra advisory pass, never a wrong verdict; the precision/decision side stays deterministic). The base reviewer is a STANDALONE agent step (not a batch criterion) so its `recommend_overlays` output survives (the batch runner aggregates only `findings`).\n\nEngine fit: requires NO core-engine change. `batch` membership is a static authored list (the fixed overlay enum) gated per-item by `when: ${{ steps.union.outputs.include_<overlay> }}` ‚Äî exactly how plan-review's finder batch toggles criteria. A `uses -> batch -> uses -> batch` chain is expressible. The only new engine-side code is two trivial deterministic scripted ops (`overlay_union`, `merge_findings`); the mechanism was proven end-to-end OFFLINE on the v3 engine (the agent's recommendation drove Round-B membership; bogus ids dropped by the enum; the cap bounded fan-out; one-hop held).\n\n## Dependencies ‚Äî what must be satisfied to implement successfully\n- SATISFIED: four-pass kernel (`3316`, closed) + consumer seam; runner + v3 engine (`e6d9`, closed); contract reviewer prompts (`da27`, closed); grounding oracle + detector registry (`8f6c`, closed).\n- INTERNAL NEW WORK (in this epic; no external blocker): secrets / High-Critical-security detectors (fail-closed) on the `8f6c` registry; the diff assembler; the overlay catalog + prompts; the two scripted ops; source separation.\n- EXTERNAL, STILL OPEN: **`d251` (AWS Gerrit + rebar MCP provisioning)** ‚Äî required ONLY for the Gerrit voter + the end-to-end dogfood ACs, NOT for the capability. `1fa8` (CI second \"Verified\" vote) is `relates_to`, out of scope for v1.\n- STALE LINK (provenance): the `blocks` from `9da1` should be read as superseded by `3316`; both `9da1`/`3316` are closed, so the only LIVE blocker is `d251`.\n\n## Why this epic is NOT split (and the alternative)\nThe code-review CAPABILITY (passes 1-4 + overlays + the deterministic verdict, exposed via the existing MCP `review_code` tool + `rebar review-code` CLI) delivers value and is FULLY TESTABLE on real diffs WITHOUT Gerrit ‚Äî so it does not need `d251`. Bundling it with the Gerrit dogfood couples a software deliverable to AWS infra on a different timeline. Rather than split the epic, the ACs below are PARTITIONED into (A) Capability ‚Äî buildable and verifiable NOW against the shipped kernel ‚Äî and (B) Dogfood/Gerrit ‚Äî gated on `d251`. This keeps one epic with one provenance trail while making the dependency boundary explicit; splitting remains an option only if the capability is to be released/closed independently of the infra.\n\n## Decisions pinned during plan-review (2026-06)\nThese resolve advisory findings the four-pass plan-review gate raised against this plan (verdict PASS):\n- **Overlay cap N = 3** to start (conservative; aligns with the orchestrator-worker \"3-5 subagents\" prior art). Calibration of N + the advisory/block thresholds is DEFERRED (shared stance with the kernel epic ‚Äî thresholds start high, so v1 is mostly advisory); the cap/threshold values live in `gates/code-review.yaml` config, not hard-coded.\n- **Secrets/security detector path (v1 default):** WRAP existing scanners behind the grounding-oracle detector envelope ‚Äî **gitleaks** for secrets, **semgrep** for High-Critical security ‚Äî as the deterministic ground-truth pre-pass (the LLM triages/prioritizes, never invents). Native first-party detectors are a follow-on, not v1. (Alternative weighed: author native detectors first ‚Äî rejected for v1 because the scanners already encode high-precision rule sets; scanner-as-ground-truth is settled production practice.)\n- **Observable verdict artifact:** the gate returns a typed `code_review_verdict` dict (`{verdict: PASS|BLOCK, blocking[], advisory[], coaching[], coverage}`) + emits a review sidecar ‚Äî exactly parallel to plan-review's verdict + sidecar, so the verdict is a checkable artifact (not just a Gerrit side effect).\n- **Re-export shim contract:** the PUBLIC SURFACE is preserved unchanged ‚Äî the `rebar.llm.review_code(...)` callable, the MCP `review_code` tool, and the `rebar review-code` CLI keep their names/signatures and continue to return a `review_result`. What changes is the IMPLEMENTATION behind that surface: the four-pass kernel-consuming gate REPLACES the single-pass `evidence + aggregate_findings`-only route, which becomes unreachable. `aggregate_findings`/`normalize_finding` may survive as internal Pass-1 helpers; the single-pass GATE PATH does not. The destructive removal of the demo path is recorded in an ADR (one-way door).\n\n## Implementation sequencing (workstreams) ‚Äî now child stories\nThe capability is decomposed into child stories (created 2026-06), sequenced via `depends_on` so each lands behind the previous one's contract. WS1 is the ready entry; WS6 is gated on `d251`.\n1. **WS1 ‚Äî diff context-assembler + base reviewer** (8e6f-3ad2-1f24-4b8b / low-cloud-wreck) ‚Äî ready now.\n2. **WS2 ‚Äî overlay catalog + finder/verify/coach prompts + code move-catalog** (8e78-d515-3a98-4eba / make-rant-buoy) ‚Äî depends_on WS1.\n3. **WS3 ‚Äî `overlay_union` + `merge_findings` ops + `gates/code-review.yaml`** (8855-e5f9-05b4-4a04 / crow-knelt-fiber) ‚Äî depends_on WS2.\n4. **WS4 ‚Äî `gate_dispatch.produce_code_review_verdict` + source-separation** (98ff-d3b8-d2f7-4a86 / side-haiku-dew) ‚Äî depends_on WS3.\n5. **WS5 ‚Äî secrets/security detectors (fail-closed)** (bba6-69b9-b9d4-4ac0 / corn-pub-oat) ‚Äî depends_on WS3.\n6. **WS6 ‚Äî Gerrit `LLM-Review` voter + dogfood** (4119-1a4f-19ff-4cfa / virid-trench-stone) ‚Äî depends_on WS4; gated on `d251`.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- The four-pass code-review capability consumes the shared `review_kernel` (no forked passes) and runs as rebar's `LLM-Review` voter in Gerrit, off by default and source-isolated (inert and unmistakably non-applicable when disabled).\n- rebar's own changes are reviewed and gated by it end-to-end through the Gerrit gate (dogfood).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\nThe internal new-work dependencies are captured here as workstream ACs; each is a CHILD STORY (detailed ACs + file-impact + verify-commands live on the child). The epic is DONE when all children are closed.\n\n### A. Capability (buildable now against the shipped kernel ‚Äî no external blocker)\n- [ ] **WS1** (8e6f-3ad2-1f24-4b8b / low-cloud-wreck) ‚Äî diff context-assembler + base reviewer emitting enum-constrained `recommend_overlays` (standalone agent step).\n- [ ] **WS2** (8e78-d515-3a98-4eba / make-rant-buoy) ‚Äî overlay catalog (specialist reviewers with `applies_to` globs/content triggers) + a code verify preamble embedding `VERIFIER_RULES_SCAFFOLD` + a code move-catalog (`MOVE_REGISTRY_SCHEMA` instance) + a `threshold_for` resolver.\n- [ ] **WS3** (8855-e5f9-05b4-4a04 / crow-knelt-fiber) ‚Äî `overlay_union` (glob U recommend ‚àí already-run, ONE-HOP, cap N=3) + `merge_findings` + the thin `gates/code-review.yaml` (two-round escalation ‚Üí kernel Pass-2/3/4); offline FakeRunner test asserts escalation/cap/one-hop and that escalation can never change the verdict.\n- [ ] **WS4** (98ff-d3b8-d2f7-4a86 / side-haiku-dew) ‚Äî `gate_dispatch.produce_code_review_verdict` returning the typed `code_review_verdict` + sidecar; OFF by default + SOURCE-SEPARATED; public surface preserved via re-export/shim; single-pass route retired (ADR).\n- [ ] **WS5** (bba6-69b9-b9d4-4ac0 / corn-pub-oat) ‚Äî secrets/security detectors (wrap gitleaks + semgrep behind the grounding-oracle envelope) feeding the hard auto-block; FAIL-CLOSED with a RED-fixture test (unavailable/errored detector BLOCKS or flags a coverage gap, never silently passes).\n\n### B. Dogfood / Gerrit (gated on `d251-05e1-eb55-43b2`)\n- [ ] **WS6** (4119-1a4f-19ff-4cfa / virid-trench-stone) ‚Äî wired as the Gerrit `LLM-Review` voter (review on patchset-created, vote via REST, block/advisory ‚Üí label); dogfood proof: at least one real rebar change reviewed + gated end-to-end on the AWS/Gerrit environment.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782620731598237001,"uuid":"bb0f7158-cf21-4b89-9ef0-04262a6b7ed4"}